  "question": "Carlos is planting a lemon tree. The tree will cost $90 to plant. Each year it will grow 7 lemons, which he can sell for $1.5 each. It costs $3 a year to water and feed the tree. How many years will it take before he starts earning money on the lemon tree?",
  "prompt": "Carlos is planting a lemon tree. The tree will cost $90 to plant. Each year it will grow 7 lemons, which he can sell for $1.5 each. It costs $3 a year to water and feed the tree. How many years will it take before he starts earning money on the lemon tree?\n\nShow your work briefly and put the final answer in \\boxed{}.",
  "gold_answer": "13",
  "generated_text": "To determine how many years it takes for Carlos to start earning money, we need to compare the initial planting cost to the total revenue generated by the lemons.\n\n**1. Identify the costs and revenues:**\n*   **Initial Cost:** $\\$90$ (one-time cost to plant).\n*   **Annual Revenue per Lemon:** $\\$1.50$.\n*   **Annual Cost (Water/Feed):** $\\$3.00$.\n*   **Lemon Yield per Year:** $7$ lemons.\n\n**2. Calculate the net profit per year:**\nFirst, find the total revenue from selling the lemons:\n$$ \\text{Revenue} = 7 \\text{ lemons/year} \\times \\$1.50/\\text{lemon} = \\$10.50 $$\n\nNext, subtract the annual operating cost:\n$$ \\text{Net Profit} = \\$10.50 - \\$3.00 = \\$7.50 \\text{ per year} $$\n\n**3. Determine the break-even point:**\nCarlos starts earning money only after the initial investment is recovered. The break-even point occurs when the accumulated profit equals the initial cost.\n$$ \\text{Years to break even} = \\frac{\\text{Initial Cost}}{\\text{Net Profit per Year}} $$\n$$ \\text{Years to break even} = \\frac{90}{7.50} $$\n\n**4. Perform the division:**\n$$ \\frac{90}{7.5} = \\frac{900}{75} $$\nDivide both numerator and denominator by 75:\n$$ \\frac{900}{75} = 12 $$\n\nSo, it takes 12 years to earn back the initial $90 investment. At this point, his net profit is $12 \\times \\$7.50 = \\$90$, which exactly matches the initial cost.\n\n\\boxed{12}\n",
